SIMPLE: outlaw
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Outlaw
<hw>Out"law`</hw> <pr>(out"l⟦add⟧`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦umac⟧tlaga</ets>, <ets>⟦umac⟧tlah</ets>. See <er>Out</er>, and
<er>Law</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person excluded from the benefit
of the law, or deprived of its protection.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person engaging habitually in criminal activity,
especially theft or robbery; an habitually lawless person, especially
one who is a fugitive from the law.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Outlaw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Outlaw
<hw>Out"law`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Outlawed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Outlawing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets><?/tlagian</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of the benefit and protection of law; to
declare to be an outlaw.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove from legal jurisdiction or enforcement;
<as>as, to <ex>outlaw</ex> a debt or claim</as>; to deprive of legal
force.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Laws <xex>outlawed</xex> by necessity.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render illegal; to ban, prohibit, or proscribe
under sanction of some penalty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>outlawed</ent>⟦br⟧
